        How to Read a Title Search When Selling Your Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A title search shows everything registered against your property. Understanding what is on it before you list can prevent delays, renegotiations, and last-minute surprises.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A title search is a snapshot of the official Queensland land register record for your property. It shows who legally owns the property, what mortgages are registered against it, and whether there are any easements, caveats, covenants, or other encumbrances that affect the land. Buyers' solicitors will order a title search early in the contract process, so anything on your title will become visible. Understanding what is there before you list gives you the opportunity to explain, correct, or resolve issues rather than having them surface mid-campaign or at the contract stage.</p>

      <p>In Queensland, title searches are conducted through the Titles Registry, which is operated by Titles Queensland. The registry uses an electronic system called e-Titles and maintains records for all freehold land in the state. A standard title search includes the current title deed, the registered plan showing the lot boundaries, and any instruments registered on the title. Your solicitor can order one on your behalf, or you can search online through the Queensland Spatial Catalogue or a commercial title search provider.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a title search shows</h2>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Registered owners.</strong> The title identifies who holds an interest in the property and in what capacity. If the property is owned jointly, it will specify whether the ownership is as joint tenants or tenants in common, and in what proportions. This matters at sale time because all registered owners need to sign the contract and the transfer documents. If there is a dispute between owners, or a registered owner has died, the title may need to be updated before a sale can proceed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mortgages.</strong> If you have a home loan, the lender's mortgage will be registered on the title. This is standard and expected. When you sell, the mortgage is discharged from the proceeds at settlement and removed from the title at the same time. What can occasionally cause issues is an old mortgage from a previous owner that was never formally discharged, or a caveat lodged by a lender after a default. Your solicitor checks for these routinely and can resolve most straightforward cases with time.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Easements.</strong> An easement gives another party a legal right to use part of your land for a specified purpose. Common easements in Brisbane's inner east include drainage easements allowing council access to stormwater infrastructure, electricity easements for power lines crossing the property, and right-of-way easements giving a neighbouring property access across yours. Easements run with the land, which means they transfer to the new owner at sale. Buyers' solicitors will examine what any easement permits and whether it affects how the property can be used or developed. Easements are not necessarily a problem, but they need to be understood and disclosed.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Covenants.</strong> A covenant is a restriction on how the land can be used or developed, imposed by a previous owner, developer, or council. Some covenants are historical and may no longer be enforceable or practically relevant. Others are actively enforced and can affect what a buyer can do with the property, including what structures they can build or what the property can be used for. Your solicitor will assess whether any covenant on the title is current and enforceable, and what it means for the sale.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Caveats.</strong> A caveat is a formal notice that someone is claiming an interest in the property. It effectively acts as a stop on the title: while a caveat is registered, dealings including a sale cannot be registered without the caveator's consent or a court order removing the caveat. Caveats can be lodged by secured creditors, people claiming an equitable interest under an unregistered agreement, or in some cases ex-spouses or business partners in dispute. Finding a caveat on your title before you list is significantly better than discovering it during a contract negotiation. Most can be resolved, but the process takes time.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Other encumbrances.</strong> The title can also show heritage designations, building management statements for unit complexes, leases, and charges registered by government authorities such as local councils or water authorities. A building management statement is relevant for units and townhouses in community title schemes and governs how shared areas are managed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common surprises sellers discover at this stage</h2>
      <p>The most frequent unexpected finding is a caveat lodged years earlier that was never removed after a dispute was resolved. A former business partner, a contractor who was not paid, or a family member who advanced funds for a purchase can all lodge caveats, and they sometimes sit on titles for years without the current owner being aware. Resolving a caveat requires either the caveator to withdraw it voluntarily, or an application to the Supreme Court, which takes weeks to months. Discovering this early leaves time to resolve it before going to market.</p>

      <p>The second common surprise is an easement that the current owner did not know existed or had forgotten about. An electricity easement running through the backyard, for example, can affect where a buyer might want to build a pool or extend. It does not prevent the sale but it is a material fact that needs to be disclosed, and an informed buyer will price it into their offer. Better to know it is there and frame it accurately than to have a buyer's solicitor raise it during the contract and create uncertainty.</p>

      <p>In older homes in Brisbane's inner east, another occasional finding is a building encroachment: a structure such as a fence, garage, or extension that was built across a boundary and does not match what is shown on the registered plan. Encroachments can affect the property's use and can complicate a sale if the neighbouring owner has not agreed to the arrangement. These are more common than most sellers expect and are usually resolvable but take legal advice to manage properly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to order a title search in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Your conveyancing solicitor will order a title search as a standard part of preparing for your sale. If you want to review the title before engaging a solicitor, you can search the Queensland Spatial Catalogue yourself using the property address or lot and plan number, which is available on your rates notice or previous conveyancing documents. Commercial title search providers also offer this service for a small fee and return results immediately.</p>

      <p>The practical advice is to engage your solicitor early in the pre-listing process, ideally four to six weeks before you plan to go to market. This gives enough time to identify and address any title issues before they affect your campaign timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What your solicitor checks for</h2>
      <p>A good conveyancing solicitor reviewing a title for an upcoming sale is looking for anything that could delay settlement, create a disclosure obligation, affect the buyer's ability to obtain finance, or reduce the property's value or utility. They will check that the registered ownership matches who is selling, confirm that any registered mortgage is held by the expected lender, identify any easements and explain their practical impact, flag any caveats or encumbrances that need to be resolved, and ensure the lot and plan details match the property description used in your contract.</p>

      <p>For straightforward titles with no unusual entries, this is a brief process. For titles with multiple easements, an old caveat, or complex ownership arrangements, it takes longer. Either way, your solicitor's job at this stage is to give you a clear picture of the title's status so you go to market with no hidden surprises.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Resolving issues before you list</h2>
      <p>Most title issues are resolvable. A caveat from a resolved dispute can be formally withdrawn. An old undischarged mortgage from a previous sale can be removed through the lender's records. An encroachment can be addressed through a boundary encroachment agreement with the neighbouring owner. The common thread is that these processes take time, sometimes several weeks, and they cannot be started until the issue is identified. A title that is clean before your campaign begins is one fewer variable to manage when buyer interest is at its peak and timing matters most.</p>

